# TypeScript Conventions

## Type imports
Always use `import type` for types and interfaces to keep runtime bundles clean:
```typescript
// ❌ BAD
import { ButtonProps } from "@/components/button";

// ✅ GOOD
import type { ButtonProps } from "@/components/button";
```

## Wrapper component types
Derive prop types from the primitive rather than redefining them:
```typescript
// ❌ BAD — duplicates the type definition
interface ButtonProps { variant?: string; size?: string; ... }

// ✅ GOOD — stays in sync automatically
type ButtonProps = React.ComponentProps<typeof ButtonPrimitive>;
```

## No `as` casting for external input
Never cast values you don't control (FormData, URL params, API responses):
```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const value = formData.get("email") as string;

// ✅ GOOD
const value = formData.get("email");
if (typeof value !== "string") { /* handle */ }
```

## Async / floating promises
All `async` functions must be awaited at the call site. The ESLint rule `@typescript-eslint/no-floating-promises` enforces this — do not disable it.

## Unused variables
Prefix intentionally unused parameters with `_`:
```typescript
function handler(_req: Request, res: Response) { ... }
```

## Avoid `any`
The ESLint config warns on `any`. If the type is genuinely unknown, use `unknown` and narrow it:
```typescript
// ❌ BAD
catch (e: any) { console.log(e.message) }

// ✅ GOOD
catch (e) {
  const message = e instanceof Error ? e.message : String(e);
}
```
